^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On this hand, by planning and not drawing trump prematurely, I was able to take the most tricks I could. I would like to discuss Ann's question about forcing bids. There is a common misconception about forcing bids. It is true that a new suit by responder is forcing. So, as long as Ann keeps bidding new suits I cannot pass. However, the same is not true of opener. A new suit by opener is not forcing. If opener wants to force responder to bid, opener must either jump shift or reverse.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If I wanted to force Ann to bid I would have to bid (on a different hand of course) either 2H  or 3C. This makes sense if you think about it. Opener often has a weakish hand, and if responder has a weakish response, you don't want to get too high. So, new suits by opener are not forcing if they are not a reverse or jump shift. Having said that, responder must still be careful because opener can have as much as 17 (as I did on this hand) and still not jump shift. Therefore, with 9+ responder should still take another bid.|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One other advertisement for the hondo style of weak-2s. Had Elizabeth opened a weak-2 (most people other than me would not), I would bid 3D, which turns out to be a bad contract.|
